<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-19T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-19T21:00:00-05:00" n="596" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d596">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11718: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-20T10:00:00+08:00">December 20, 1937—10
                                    a.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 20—1 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>90. My 87, December 20 [<hi rend="italic">19</hi>], 10 a.m. [<hi rend="italic">2 p.m.</hi>].<note n="27" xml:id="d596fn27"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_404">p.
                                404</ref>.</note> Have just received official notification from
                            Foreign Office stating river has been effectively blocked below Kiukiang
                            as of 12 noon today. Steamer connection between Hankow and Shanghai now
                            cut off. Communication by rail and air remains.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Peiping, Shanghai. Peiping repeat to Tokyo.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>